00:01:51.190 --> 00:01:54.660
So let's start by defining what
do we mean here at Google when

00:01:54.660 --> 00:01:57.510
we say accessibility?

00:01:57.510 --> 00:02:02.510
And accessibility refers to the
designs of products, devices,

00:02:02.510 --> 00:02:06.648
services, or environments that
works to include everybody.

00:02:06.648 --> 00:02:08.440
And what you'll hopefully
see is that we've

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:10.960
tried to bring the
principles of this statement

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:12.623
into our deck today.

00:02:12.623 --> 00:02:15.040
So you're going to see things
like clear and simple slides

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:17.170
to convey our
messaging, high color

00:02:17.170 --> 00:02:19.990
contrast for the optimal
visual experience.

00:02:19.990 --> 00:02:22.600
We're going to do our very
best to try and talk and pace

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:23.680
slowly.

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:25.835
So that can be sometimes
a problem from people

00:02:25.835 --> 00:02:26.710
who live in New York.

00:02:26.710 --> 00:02:29.760
So bear with us.

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:33.460
And according to the World
Health Organization, about 15%

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:36.240
of the world lives with
some sort of disability.

00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:40.210
That's over 1 billion
people, over 1 billion people

00:02:40.210 --> 00:02:42.100
who require some
sort of accessibility

00:02:42.100 --> 00:02:46.230
need to live their
everyday lives.

00:02:46.230 --> 00:02:47.880
And accessibility
needs may be caused

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:51.480
by disabilities that are
temporary or situational

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:54.120
such as being deaf
or hard of hearing,

00:02:54.120 --> 00:02:56.220
having some sort of
motor impairment,

00:02:56.220 --> 00:02:58.140
having some sort of
cognitive disability

00:02:58.140 --> 00:03:00.480
that might impede
learning, or blindness

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:02.238
and visual impairments.

00:03:02.238 --> 00:03:03.780
And I think it's
probably safe to say

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:06.690
that most folks in
this room have either

00:03:06.690 --> 00:03:10.110
been directly or
indirectly impacted

00:03:10.110 --> 00:03:11.850
by one of these categories.

00:03:11.850 --> 00:03:13.890
I know both Max and I
have personally been,

00:03:13.890 --> 00:03:17.332
which is why we're excited to be
here talking to you guys today.

00:03:17.332 --> 00:03:18.790
And we wanted to
take a moment just

00:03:18.790 --> 00:03:22.180
to zoom in on one of those
categories, a category that's

00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:25.090
probably most relevant
for the folks in this room

00:03:25.090 --> 00:03:27.730
if you're creating
touch app experiences.

00:03:27.730 --> 00:03:31.120
And that's looking at the
over 250 million people

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:33.220
who live with some sort
of visual impairment

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:34.722
on a daily basis.

00:03:34.722 --> 00:03:37.180
And we really just wanted to
give you a little more context

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:41.240
to the size of that user base,
to the size of that audience.

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:43.200
And if you look at that
number, that number

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:45.820
is larger than the
country of Brazil.

00:03:45.820 --> 00:03:48.710
It would be the fifth largest
country behind Indonesia

00:03:48.710 --> 00:03:50.200
and the United States.

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:52.660
And that number doesn't
even take into account

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:55.810
the additional
342 million people

00:03:55.810 --> 00:04:00.510
that live with some sort of
colorblindness every day.

00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:02.760
And creating an app
experience that's

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:05.460
accessible for your
users not only helps

00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:06.845
folks with disabilities.

00:04:06.845 --> 00:04:08.970
But think of a time in your
life where maybe you've

00:04:08.970 --> 00:04:11.850
had an inaccessible experience,
either with your favorite app

00:04:11.850 --> 00:04:16.200
or game or just with
life in general.

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:18.370
And beyond disabilities,
accessibility

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:19.982
can be very situational.

00:04:19.982 --> 00:04:21.399
Think of a time
where maybe you've

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:23.066
been in a crowded
restaurant, and you're

00:04:23.066 --> 00:04:25.297
trying to hear audio
or a conversation.

00:04:25.297 --> 00:04:27.130
Or maybe you're in a
low lighting situation.

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:29.422
And you haven't been able to
see your phone or your app

00:04:29.422 --> 00:04:31.452
or anything in the
way you wanted to.

00:04:31.452 --> 00:04:33.160
Or think of a time
where you've just been

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:35.350
frustrated in any situation.

00:04:35.350 --> 00:04:36.700
Maybe you're holding a baby.

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:38.410
Maybe you're holding
a bag of groceries.

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:39.723
Maybe you're holding anything.

00:04:39.723 --> 00:04:41.890
And you haven't been able
to interact with something

00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:44.510
the way that you want to
or the way you expect to.

00:04:44.510 --> 00:04:47.820
It can be very frustrating.

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:50.250
And when we talk to our
developer ecosystem,

00:04:50.250 --> 00:04:53.580
we often hear that accessibility
is top of mind and something

00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:55.570
that they're looking
to prioritize.

00:04:55.570 --> 00:04:58.410
But we found a much different
and frankly, a little scarier,

00:04:58.410 --> 00:05:03.240
result when we ran our quarterly
developer satisfaction survey.

00:05:03.240 --> 00:05:06.180
And during that survey, we
asked our developer ecosystem

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:08.640
how they were approaching
accessibility, and more

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:11.310
importantly, how they were
approaching accessibility use

00:05:11.310 --> 00:05:14.080
cases and how they
were testing for them.

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:16.680
And what we found
is that nearly 80%

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:19.500
of the ecosystems
who responded said

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:22.590
that they don't accommodate
for accessibility at all.

00:05:22.590 --> 00:05:25.560
Obviously, that's something that
both Max and I want to change,

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:28.320
both by bringing more awareness
to the topic, the importance

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:31.200
of the topic, as well as
outlining all the great tools

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:33.630
and resources that you
as developers can start

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:35.850
to take advantage of to
create more accessible

00:05:35.850 --> 00:05:38.280
and inclusive experiences.

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:40.292
And the good news is is
that we're here to help.

00:05:40.292 --> 00:05:42.750
And so I wanted to walk you
guys through the three sections

00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:44.740
that we're going
to touch on today.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:47.220
And the first one is really
that accessibility is

00:05:47.220 --> 00:05:49.308
built into Google's core DNA.

00:05:49.308 --> 00:05:50.850
And so Max is going
to take some time

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:52.470
to walk you through
