00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:18.210
to ensure that accessibility
is being prioritized

00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:20.730
and is top of mind
for the ecosystem.

00:06:20.730 --> 00:06:23.420
And with that, I'm going
to hand it over to Max.

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:24.930
MAXIM MAI: Cheers, Brandon.

00:06:24.930 --> 00:06:28.320
At Google, one of our
guiding philosophies

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:30.870
is to organize the
world's information

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:34.350
and make it universally
accessible and useful.

00:06:34.350 --> 00:06:37.450
Well, the Android team has
really taken the accessible

00:06:37.450 --> 00:06:38.640
part to heart.

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:40.680
So I'm going to walk
you through just a few

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:44.440
of the examples that make
Android more accessible.

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:49.060
First off, out of the
250 million users with--

00:06:49.060 --> 00:06:53.260
people in the world with
visual impairments, 36 million

00:06:53.260 --> 00:06:55.390
are legally blind.

00:06:55.390 --> 00:06:59.200
These users can use technologies
such as screen readers

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:02.650
or Braille displays to
access their Android devices.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:08.310
Because of these
technologies, this

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:11.400
is how a blind user
might dim their screen

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:14.460
to increase their
privacy but retain

00:07:14.460 --> 00:07:18.650
full usability of their phone.

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:21.640
TalkBack, which is
Google's screen reader,

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:25.240
will add spoken
and haptic feedback

00:07:25.240 --> 00:07:28.210
to your device to make
it usable without ever

00:07:28.210 --> 00:07:30.310
looking at the screen.

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:32.610
In the next section, Brandon
will talk a little bit

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:35.880
about what you can do to make
your app work really well

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:38.250
with screen readers.

00:07:38.250 --> 00:07:42.990
Select to Speak helps the
over 200 million people

00:07:42.990 --> 00:07:47.850
who have mid to severe
vision impairments.

00:07:47.850 --> 00:07:49.980
So what you can do if
you have TalkBack--

00:07:49.980 --> 00:07:54.000
if you have Select to Speak
enabled, you touch your screen.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.210
And the phone reads
back to you or describes

00:07:57.210 --> 00:08:00.200
what you have touched.

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:05.750
As it turns out, Select to Speak
is also super useful for people

00:08:05.750 --> 00:08:10.320
who have difficulty processing
written or visual information

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:12.170
or who have learning
disabilities.

00:08:14.690 --> 00:08:20.260
Many Android users suffer from
motor disabilities or motor

00:08:20.260 --> 00:08:21.670
impairments.

00:08:21.670 --> 00:08:26.710
So this can range from partial
to total paralysis, limited

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:30.070
dexterity in the
hands or fingers,

00:08:30.070 --> 00:08:32.919
as well as limited mobility.

00:08:32.919 --> 00:08:36.100
There are various technologies
that help these users interact

00:08:36.100 --> 00:08:40.690
with their devices such as
keyboard access or voice

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:45.610
control or head tracking
or eye tracking.

00:08:45.610 --> 00:08:48.650
Another technology
is Switch Access.

00:08:48.650 --> 00:08:50.840
So a switch, it's very simple.

00:08:50.840 --> 00:08:54.350
It's basically a big button that
you can press with your hand

00:08:54.350 --> 00:08:56.310
or with your head.

00:08:56.310 --> 00:08:58.125
And you can fully
control your device.

