broader documentation.

00:12:49.910 --> 00:12:52.820
But it also has a number
of best practices, things

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:54.740
like ensuring that
you're labeling your UI

00:12:54.740 --> 00:12:58.130
elements correctly so that
your app works with things

00:12:58.130 --> 00:13:01.490
like screen readers, making
sure that you have large touch

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:03.950
targets so that folks
with motor impairments

00:13:03.950 --> 00:13:08.270
or like me, have fumbly fingers,
can easily navigate your app,

00:13:08.270 --> 00:13:10.700
and ensuring that you're
providing proper color

00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:14.240
contrast so that users with
low vision who might be using

00:13:14.240 --> 00:13:18.778
their screens dimmed can have
the optimal viewing experience.

00:13:18.778 --> 00:13:20.570
And I think the important
part to note here

00:13:20.570 --> 00:13:22.970
is that a lot of
these updates don't

00:13:22.970 --> 00:13:27.260
necessitate code restructuring
or heavy dev resources.

00:13:27.260 --> 00:13:28.970
Rather, it's taking
a moment to think

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:32.480
through the subtle details
of how users are interacting

00:13:32.480 --> 00:13:35.390
and using your app and ensuring
that you're providing them

00:13:35.390 --> 00:13:38.760
with that experience.

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:41.160
And here at Google, as I hope
most folks in this audience

00:13:41.160 --> 00:13:43.080
know, we have Material Design.

00:13:43.080 --> 00:13:45.270
Material Design is
our design language

00:13:45.270 --> 00:13:47.790
which combines the
principles of good design

00:13:47.790 --> 00:13:49.500
with science and technology.

00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:52.140
And within our broader
Material Design overviews

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:55.170
and material.io, we also
have an entire section

00:13:55.170 --> 00:13:57.300
dedicated to accessibility.

00:13:57.300 --> 00:13:59.160
And within that
section, we outline

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:02.730
how developers can create
really clear, robust,

00:14:02.730 --> 00:14:07.410
and specific experiences so your
users can navigate and utilize

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:10.140
the app the way that
they want to use it

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:12.120
and the way that it's
meant to be used.

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:14.620
So we'd encourage you to
head over to material.io

00:14:14.620 --> 00:14:18.330
and check it out.

00:14:18.330 --> 00:14:22.330
And probably the most key
and important component

00:14:22.330 --> 00:14:25.210
within this process to make
an accessible experience

00:14:25.210 --> 00:14:27.310
is testing your app.

00:14:27.310 --> 00:14:30.530
Encourage you to test,
test, test, and test again.

00:14:30.530 --> 00:14:32.500
So within the
guidelines, we've also

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:34.360
published a getting
started guide

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:37.300
which outlines the different
methodologies and the ways you

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:38.200
can take--

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:40.930
go about testing your
app's accessibility.

00:14:40.930 --> 00:14:43.480
And what we found is that
the most accessible apps

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:45.370
have really taken
advantage of all three

00:14:45.370 --> 00:14:48.040
of these different methodologies
to ensure that nothing

00:14:48.040 --> 00:14:50.260
is missed when it
comes to the usability

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:53.722
and accessibility of your app.

00:14:53.722 --> 00:14:55.180
And here at Google,
folks might not

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:57.700
be aware that we also have
a first party app called

00:14:57.700 --> 00:14:59.690
the Accessibility Scanner.

00:14:59.690 --> 00:15:02.200
The Accessibility Scanner
is available to download

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:04.540
on the Play Store and
can be used with anybody

00:15:04.540 --> 00:15:06.490
without technical background.

00:15:06.490 --> 00:15:07.960
You download the app.

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:10.870
And it scans the
accessibility capabilities

00:15:10.870 --> 00:15:13.740
on any app you already have
downloaded on your phone.

00:15:13.740 --> 00:15:16.270
And it helps identify
things like touch target

00:15:16.270 --> 00:15:21.058
sizes, low color contrast,
content labeling, and more.

00:15:21.058 --> 00:15:22.600
And what it does is
that it gives you

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:25.540
subtle suggestions on
how to improve that

00:15:25.540 --> 00:15:28.553
or it points you to the proper
resources to address it.

00:15:28.553 --> 00:15:30.970
So again, we encourage you to
head over to the Play Store,

00:15:30.970 --> 00:15:34.640
give it a download, and start
playing around with it today.

00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:36.830
And finally, as we talked
about earlier today,

00:15:36.830 --> 00:15:39.770
we have the pre-launch reports,
which help our developers

00:15:39.770 --> 00:15:42.500
as they upload their
APKs or their app bundles

00:15:42.500 --> 00:15:46.310
to identify a number
of different issues

00:15:46.310 --> 00:15:48.500
across a number of
different Android devices

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:53.120
before your app goes public,
including accessibility.

00:15:53.120 --> 00:15:54.710
And since launching
accessibility

00:15:54.710 --> 00:15:57.230
in the pre-launch
reports this past July,

00:15:57.230 --> 00:15:59.960
we've helped flag
over 35 million issues

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:02.660
across 500,000 apps.

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:05.550
And while this seems like
a fairly large number,

00:16:05.550 --> 00:16:08.000
I think the thing to point out
here is that a lot of these

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.100
are very simple fixes,
things that you're

00:16:10.100 --> 00:16:12.797
able to fix before you
publish your app publicly.

00:16:12.797 --> 00:16:14.630
And so we again encourage
you to take a look

00:16:14.630 --> 00:16:16.880
at the pre-launch reports
around accessibility

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:19.160
to ensure you're providing
your users with the most

00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:21.410
inclusive and
accessible experience.

00:16:21.410 --> 00:16:22.910
With that, I'm going
to hand it back

00:16:22.910 --> 00:16:24.740
to Max who's going to
talk about what we're

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:27.020
doing throughout the rest
of the year and into 2019

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:30.230
around accessibility.

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:31.760
MAXIM MAI: Cheers, Brandon.

00:16:31.760 --> 00:16:36.770
Some of you may be wondering,
well, this looks beneficial.

00:16:36.770 --> 00:16:44.740
But how much work is this going
to be for me or for my team?

00:16:44.740 --> 00:16:51.440
Also, how will I be able to
prioritize this on my roadmap?

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:55.940
Well, we were thinking exactly
the same earlier this year.

00:16:55.940 --> 00:16:58.100
And we decided to take a look.

00:16:58.100 --> 00:17:01.870
So I'm going to walk
you through what

00:17:01.870 --> 00:17:04.180
we've done since this summer.

00:17:04.180 --> 00:17:07.599
In fact, we got together
with a couple of you.

00:17:07.599 --> 00:17:10.540
We got together
with 19 developers

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:13.760
from all the global regions.

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:17.609
And we did a Play
accessibility review pilot.

00:17:17.609 --> 00:17:19.109
And we wanted to do two things.

00:17:19.109 --> 00:17:21.470
We wanted to
understand and learn

00:17:21.470 --> 00:17:27.410
how can we review apps for
accessibility at scale.

00:17:27.410 --> 00:17:30.800
And more importantly,
we wanted to understand

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:35.010
how difficult would
it be for developers

00:17:35.010 --> 00:17:40.050
to make fixes to make
their app more accessible.

00:17:40.050 --> 00:17:43.480
And so here are the results.

00:17:43.480 --> 00:17:46.480
Here you'll see
the top nine issues

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:49.440
that were discovered
during the pilot.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:52.350
You can see the
frequency by which

00:17:52.350 --> 00:17:58.470
they were discovered on the
y-axis and the difficulty

00:17:58.470 --> 00:18:01.890
of fixing them on the x-axis.

00:18:01.890 --> 00:18:04.530
And I think the
key takeaway here

00:18:04.530 --> 00:18:11.230
is that a lot of the frequent
fixes were easily fixed.

00:18:11.230 --> 00:18:14.360
But I want to look at the
two most frequent fixes--

00:18:14.360 --> 00:18:19.470
two most frequent issues in
a little bit more detail.

00:18:19.470 --> 00:18:22.840
So let's look at
an issue that was

00:18:22.840 --> 00:18:25.790
seen in almost every
single app we reviewed

00:18:25.790 --> 00:18:28.760
during the pilot,
which is missing

00:18:28.760 --> 00:18:34.130
or ambiguous hints and labels.

00:18:34.130 --> 00:18:37.730
So imagine you're using
your phone, and you're blind

00:18:37.730 --> 00:18:39.410
or you have severe
vision impairment,

00:18:39.410 --> 00:18:43.290
and you're using
a screen reader.

00:18:43.290 --> 00:18:46.600
And focus on the
search box at the top.

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:53.940
So the screen reader would read
this as try Beijing edit box.

00:18:53.940 --> 00:18:57.000
And if you don't have any
visual context, as a user,

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.180
you would not know
that this is where

00:18:59.180 --> 00:19:03.030
you go to search for
your next destination.

00:19:03.030 --> 00:19:07.330
The fix for this is actually
super, super simple.

00:19:07.330 --> 00:19:10.050
All you would have to do is
change the hint text here

00:19:10.050 --> 00:19:14.280
and maybe call it something like
search for a place to visit.

00:19:14.280 --> 00:19:17.100
And immediately, users
of screen readers

00:19:17.100 --> 00:19:21.960
would have a much easier
time navigating your app.

00:19:21.960 --> 00:19:25.620
The really cool thing
here is that this also

00:19:25.620 --> 00:19:28.710
improves the usability
for any user of your app,

00:19:28.710 --> 00:19:31.920
not just users of screen
readers because it's clearer

00:19:31.920 --> 00:19:34.890
what you intend this box to do.

00:19:34.890 --> 00:19:39.450
By the way, we've anonymized
all of these examples because

00:19:39.450 --> 00:19:43.900
of the sensitive nature of
the accessibility topic.

00:19:43.900 --> 00:19:49.176
So these are real examples, but
you won't recognize the apps.

00:19:49.176 --> 00:19:54.910
Now the second problem, which
was the second most frequent

00:19:54.910 --> 00:19:59.950
during the pilot, is that
users of screen readers

00:19:59.950 --> 00:20:04.370
were losing context
because of the focus order

00:20:04.370 --> 00:20:08.710
with which the screen readers
are going through the apps.

00:20:08.710 --> 00:20:14.470
Now the issue here is that if
you're using linear navigation,

00:20:14.470 --> 00:20:17.470
it may result in
your focus falling

00:20:17.470 --> 00:20:23.660
on secondary actions like
Share or Save to Favorites

00:20:23.660 --> 00:20:26.930
before the focus order
comes to the main title

00:20:26.930 --> 00:20:29.750
or the main element of the card.

00:20:29.750 --> 00:20:32.050
And so as a screen
reader user, I

00:20:32.050 --> 00:20:37.300
don't know what I'm saving to
Favorites or what I'm sharing.

00:20:37.300 --> 00:20:38.200
So that's confusing.

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:40.130
That's an issue.

00:20:40.130 --> 00:20:44.120
The fix-- we classified it,
I think, as medium to hard--

00:20:44.120 --> 00:20:50.660
is you modify the focus order
for navigating your content

00:20:50.660 --> 00:20:51.920
elements.

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:55.070
And then you land-- the focus
lands on the main element

00:20:55.070 --> 00:20:55.730
first.

00:20:55.730 --> 00:20:58.040
And then the user can
Save to Favorites.

00:20:58.040 --> 00:20:59.660
And they'll know why
they're doing it.

00:21:04.720 --> 00:21:09.130
So one thing to think about
with accessibility fixes

00:21:09.130 --> 00:21:14.340
is how easy is it to make
the app more accessible.

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:18.770
The other angle you could take
is well, what's my motivation?

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:23.600
How does accessibility fit
into my company's mission?

00:21:23.600 --> 00:21:28.400
So Lyft, the ride sharing
app, the mobility app,

00:21:28.400 --> 00:21:30.170
was one of the
pilot participants.

00:21:30.170 --> 00:21:32.690
And we asked them what
is your motivation

00:21:32.690 --> 00:21:37.490
for participating in this pilot
for investing in accessibility?

00:21:37.490 --> 00:21:40.430
And the interesting answer
that we got is well,

00:21:40.430 --> 00:21:44.090
our core mission is
improving people's lives

00:21:44.090 --> 00:21:46.670
through the world's
best transportation.

00:21:46.670 --> 00:21:51.110
And we think that having
a highly accessible app

00:21:51.110 --> 00:21:53.610
is part of that mission.

00:21:53.610 --> 00:21:57.260
And so they're using that
to justify their investment

00:21:57.260 --> 00:22:00.570
and doubling down on making
their app more accessible.

00:22:00.570 --> 00:22:02.610
And I think that's a
really nice story to share.

00:22:02.610 --> 00:22:04.490
So if you're
thinking about this,

00:22:04.490 --> 00:22:06.270
think about how it
fits into your mission.

00:22:10.030 --> 00:22:16.270
Now the accessibility pilot
was a really good experience

00:22:16.270 --> 00:22:17.830
and a very good
learning experience

00:22:17.830 --> 00:22:21.700
for both us at Play as
well as for the developers

00:22:21.700 --> 00:22:23.080
that participated.

00:22:23.080 --> 00:22:27.950
But we realized that this
was just the first step.

00:22:27.950 --> 00:22:32.330
So going forward, we're
going to double down.

00:22:32.330 --> 00:22:34.210
The first thing
we're doing is we're

00:22:34.210 --> 00:22:39.700
including accessibility feedback
in all platform design reviews

00:22:39.700 --> 00:22:41.550
that Play will do.

00:22:41.550 --> 00:22:45.010
For those of you who don't
know, a platform design review

00:22:45.010 --> 00:22:48.010
is similar but more
extensive than the review

00:22:48.010 --> 00:22:51.710
we do when we feature
apps on the Store.

00:22:51.710 --> 00:22:55.210
So now, you can ask for this
and have your app reviewed

00:22:55.210 --> 00:22:56.770
for accessibility.

00:22:56.770 --> 00:22:59.230
And we'll send you
really easy to digest

00:22:59.230 --> 00:23:02.080
feedback and suggestions.

00:23:02.080 --> 00:23:05.890
The second thing we're
doing starting in 2019,

00:23:05.890 --> 00:23:08.620
we're going to provide
further opportunities

00:23:08.620 --> 00:23:13.060
for highly accessible apps to
be discovered on the Store.

00:23:13.060 --> 00:23:17.260
This may mean that when we
make editorial decisions

00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:21.070
that we look at how
accessible is this app when

00:23:21.070 --> 00:23:22.960
we decide to feature.

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:24.670
And the other thing
that we're doing

00:23:24.670 --> 00:23:27.400
is we're investigating
how to surface

00:23:27.400 --> 00:23:31.800
highly accessible apps in
search and throughout the Store.

00:23:37.070 --> 00:23:39.920
Well, preparing
for this session,

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:45.560
we met a bunch of very, very
amazing and dedicated people

00:23:45.560 --> 00:23:48.050
who are working on accessible.

00:23:48.050 --> 00:23:52.460
It was inspiring to see their
passion as well as the progress

00:23:52.460 --> 00:23:54.760
that they've made.

00:23:54.760 --> 00:23:57.780
So I wanted to say or we
wanted to say a big thank

00:23:57.780 --> 00:24:00.450
you, all, for joining
and taking the time

00:24:00.450 --> 00:24:04.390
to learn about this
very important topic.

00:24:04.390 --> 00:24:07.950
And if you were not working
on accessibility before or not

00:24:07.950 --> 00:24:10.410
prioritizing it,
we really, really

00:24:10.410 --> 00:24:13.455
hope that we inspired
you to take action.

00:24:15.780 --> 00:24:17.280
BRANDON BARRAS: And
